properties.name: Vastrap
properties.desc: South Africa's proposed underground nuclear test area.  Two shafts were dug on either side of the runway, and after being discovered by Soviet intelligence, were filled back in, never used.  SA later dismantled their bomb making efforts.

properties.name: Yucca Mountain
properties.desc: Yucca Mountain radioactive disposal site.  This is the north entrance; the south entrance is about 1.7 miles ssw.

properties.name: EPA's NTS Dairy
properties.desc: A dairy and pig farm maintained from 1964 to 1984 by the EPA, mainly to provide experimental data for uptake of milk contamination, following Operation Schooner.

properties.name: A Tunnel, Area 16
properties.desc: Shoshone Mountain, Tunnel A Entrance.

properties.name: U16b, Divine Strake
properties.desc: U16b tunnel entrance complex, including Divine Strake proposed 700t chemical blast tunnel on the north, the latter heavily protested, delayed and eventually abandoned.

properties.name: DAF
properties.desc: Device Assembly Facility: bombs and components are made ready for testing here.

properties.name: Doomtown
properties.desc: Doomtown: the town too tough to die, the original effects test area and close cousin to SurvivalTown I and II and the town in the 3rd Indiana Jones movie.

properties.name: Plutonium Valley
properties.desc: Area contains scattered raw plutonium from plutonium dispersal safety tests.

properties.name: Radioactive Waste

properties.name: BREN Tower
properties.desc: The BREN (Bare Reactor Experiment, Nevada) is a 453m tall tower originally in Yucca Flat, used to experimentally irradiate ground targets with gamma and neutrons.  Moved to Jackass Flat, for HENRE (High Energy Neutrons Action Experiment).

properties.name: E-MAD Building
properties.desc: Engine Maintenance and Disassembly Building, used for handling radioactive NERVA engines.

properties.name: ETS-1 Test Stand
properties.desc: Engineering Test Stand 1, a stand for testing nuclear rockets in a standard upright position.

properties.name: KIWI-TNT
properties.desc: Test of the Nerva engine to destruction, to determine worst case scenario for runaway reactor.  1.6 Mci released.

properties.name: MX Testing Area
properties.desc: MX missile test track and silo

properties.name: Nerva Test Stand
properties.desc: Test stand for the nuclear rocket "Nerva".

properties.name: Project Pluto
properties.desc: Nuclear cruise missile engine development project

properties.name: R-MAD Building
properties.desc: Reactor Maintenance and Disassembly Building, maintained radioactive NERVA reactors.  Also used in the MX program.

properties.desc: The third suspended test was Operation Greenwater, the final test of the space X-Ray laser system, a part of the Star Wars concept.  The tower remains on the site.

properties.name: P Tunnel, Area 12
properties.desc: Rainier Mesa, Tunnel P Entrance.

properties.name: T Tunnel, Area 12
properties.desc: Rainier Mesa, Tunnel T Entrance.

properties.name: Annie Emplacement
properties.desc: Probable location of Atomic Annie emplacement for Grable test.

properties.name: Apple-2 houses
properties.desc: Three "typical American" houses built for the Apple-2 civil defense event.  The one on the left is 1.5 miles from the 29kt blast, the right one 2 miles.  The left one is on the monthly tour bus route.  The two towers are from later seismic studies.

properties.name: Area 3 RWMS
properties.desc: Low level Radioactive Waste Management Facility.  Waste (mostly dirt) is buried in a selection of old subsidence craters.

properties.name: Atlas Pulse Power
properties.desc: The Atlas Pulse Power Facility

properties.name: BACHUS Site
properties.desc: Biotechnology Activity Characterization by Unconventional Signatures, a secret biowarfare simulation facility.

properties.name: BEEF
properties.desc: Big Explosives Experimental Facility

properties.name: Industrial Area
properties.desc: Houses the $20 million worth of mining tools; contains area for creating site grout and stemming mixes.

properties.name: JASPER
properties.desc: Houses the Joint Actinide Shock Physics Experimental Research, a two stage light gas gun for shock experiments.

properties.name: Lockheed-Martin AOF
properties.desc: Aerial Operations Facility

properties.name: News Nob
properties.desc: The location from which VIPs and news people would watch nuclear tests.

properties.name: Operation Fortune
properties.desc: Preparation for Operation Fortune suspended.  Site reused for Unicorn subcritical test in 2005-2006.

properties.name: Operation Gabbs
properties.desc: Operation Gabbs was another shaft detonation scheduled for 1993 that was laid to rest by the test ban treaty.

properties.name: Operation Icecap
properties.desc: Operation Icecap was being built up when the 1992 Comprehensive Test Ban was signed.  The equipment was left in place: the .5 million pound instrumentation payload, the crane, the wiring, and many of the recording trailers.

properties.name: Original BREN
properties.desc: Original site of the Bare Reactor Experiment in Nevada (BREN), a reactor on a tower which emulated bomb explosions for medical studies.  A Japanese village was consructed around it because it focused on war bomb injuries.  BREN was later moved to Area 26.

properties.name: Rad/NucCTEC
properties.desc: Radiological/Nuclear Countermeasures Test and Evaluation Complex Homeland Security operational nuclear test and training center

properties.name: SurvivalTown I
properties.desc: Apparently the early NTS had ideas of parallel weapon effects test sites: the testing was pretty much parallel: Upshot-Knothole/Nancy (3/53) and Simon (4/53), Teapot/Apple I (3/55) and Apple II (5/55),  nearby Snapper/Fox and Easy (5/52), all tower shots.

properties.name: SurvivalTown II
properties.desc: The alterative to Doomtown.  Used in the Teapot Desert/Rock exercises, and the Civil Defence/PR effort Operation Cue, recycled as an equipment staging area.

properties.name: U1a
properties.desc: Main entrance to Low Yield Nuclear Explosive Research (LYNER) Complex, named after the shaft location: U1a.  In an expanding web of locations at -300 meters, destructive, but not critical, experiments continue to explore plutonium and update science.

properties.name: U1g
properties.desc: Ventilation shaft and instrumentation cabling for  LYNER Complex, U1a underground physics lab.

properties.name: U1h
properties.desc: Secondary entrance into the LYNER Complex, U1a underground lab.

properties.name: Baikonur
properties.desc: Rocket test area.

properties.name: Shary-Shagan
properties.desc: ABM ground test area.  Target area for high altitude launches #88, 115 and K series, except K3.

properties.name: Kapustin Yar
properties.desc: Rocket test area, launch area for vertical tests #88 and 115, and the K series high altitude tests over Kazakhstan.

properties.name: Razrez Mine
properties.desc: Entry to test tunnel.

properties.name: URDF-3
properties.desc: "Unidentified R and D Facility 3" is the Soviet equivalent to the US's nuclear rocket facility on Jackass Flat in the NTS.  Still in use for materials testing.

properties.name: Pollux Subcritical Experiment
properties.desc:
NNSA Conducts Pollux Subcritical Experiment at Nevada National Security SiteDec 6, 2012 | Link

The National Nuclear Security Administration (NNSA) today announced that Pollux, a subcritical experiment, was successfully conducted yesterday at its Nevada National Security Site (NNSS).

The experiment, conducted by staff from NNSS, Los Alamos National Laboratory and Sandia National Laboratories, gathered scientific data that will provide crucial information to maintain the safety and effectiveness of the nation’s nuclear weapons.

“Challenging subcritical experiments maintain our capabilities to ensure that we can support a safe, secure and effective stockpile without having to conduct underground testing,” said NNSA Administrator Thomas D’Agostino. “I applaud the work done by the men and women who worked to make this experiment successful. Experiments such as this help deliver President Obama’s nuclear security agenda.”Pollux was the 27th subcritical experiment to date. The previous subcritical experiment, Barolo B, was conducted on Feb. 2, 2011. Pollux employed a superb new diagnostic that recently won an R&D 100 award.

“Diagnostic equipment fielded by our scientists resulted in more data collected in this single experiment than all other previous subcritical experiments,” said NNSA Deputy Administrator for Defense Programs Don Cook. “This type of data is critical for ensuring our computer simulations can accurately predict performance, and thus continued confidence in the safety and effectiveness of the nation’s stockpile.”

Christopher Deeney, NNSA Assistant Deputy Administrator for Stockpile Stewardship said, “Pollux will provide a significant data set to verify codes important to laboratories' stockpile missions.”

Subcritical experiments examine the behavior of plutonium as it is strongly shocked by forces produced by chemical high explosives. Subcritical experiments produce essential scientific data and technical information used to help maintain the safety and effectiveness of the nuclear weapons stockpile. The experiments are subcritical; that is, no critical mass is formed and no self-sustaining nuclear chain reaction can occur; thus, there is no nuclear explosion.

Watch a video of the experiment on YouTube.

  • US nuclear test condemned by Iran, Japan | Link
  • Pollux: Subcritical Underground US Nuclear Explosion Test | Link
  • USA conducted subcritical non nuclear underground explosion Pollux on the range in Nevada | Video
